The main aim of this study was to acknowledge errors in this dataset to that extend that we will be able to choose a right volume threshold and other related restraints for our clustering analysis¶

A significant number of errors was found in this dataset. Initially, we tried to identify all errors throughout the dataset. Subsequently, we tried to determine whether the errors are related to only inner or surface parts of the sculpture.¶

We were able to find multiple errors most likely related to the very small size of particles that could have led to both scanning errors and following errors during the preprocessing of the scans.¶

Two main data related issues were encountered in this dataset. First error was linked to the shape in terms of violating fixed range of values between 0 and 1 for anisotropy, elongation and flatness. Second issue represents so called outliers that are any values distant from the other values in the dataset. In our case should be noted that most natural materials, such as sands or silts, do not feature such extreme particle shapes (elongation and flatness features), as these tend to break in nature, and evolve into smaller, more regular fragments (https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0032591021009785#fig0040)¶

1. All atributes¶

As we can see below that the minimum values for anisotropy, elongation and flatness are clearly erroneous since all these characteristics are used for describing the morfology of the particles, ranging between 0 and 1 (T. ZinggBeitrag Zur SchotteranalyseETH Zurich, Switzerland (1935))¶

we can also identify outliers using the following formulas for the lower and upper boundary respectively: lower= Q1 - (1.5IQR), upper=Q3+(1.5IQR), where Q1=first quartile, Q3=third quartile and IQR=interquartile range.¶
